are going through a bit of a tough time.

43:41.996 --> 43:45.329
And I want you to know
we really appreciate you trying to help.

43:45.500 --> 43:48.242
- I'm not trying to help.
- You're a loud whisperer.

43:48.419 --> 43:50.284
You shouldn't spy on people.

43:50.463 --> 43:52.328
Why have you been meeting Graham?

43:52.507 --> 43:56.466
Graham is an old friend and has had
relationship problems with Kim-Lin.

43:56.636 --> 43:58.501
He needed someone he could talk to.

43:58.679 --> 44:01.386
- So he might be single soon?
- Goodbye, Oliver.

44:06.270 --> 44:07.305
- Mum?
- Yes?

44:07.480 --> 44:08.890
Who would you save first in a fire,

44:09.065 --> 44:12.603
given the hypothetical situation that
Dad and I were equally hard to save?

44:13.236 --> 44:15.693
I'd go for you but I'd feel bad
for your father.

44:15.863 --> 44:17.728
OK.

44:32.880 --> 44:34.745
- Kiss me!
- What?

44:35.925 --> 44:38.132
I still can't believe you
fucking said it.

44:38.302 --> 44:41.169
I did not say it in a high-pitched...
like a little mouse.

44:41.347 --> 44:43.429
- You cried it.
- Come on, we're late.

44:46.602 --> 44:49.514
- That gap gets smaller every day.
- What are you doing tonight?

44:49.689 --> 44:51.350
I'm busy tonight.

44:51.524 --> 44:52.934
Doing what?

44:53.109 --> 44:54.770
As in, I've got stuff to do. Busy.

44:54.944 --> 44:57.651
No, you never have anything to do.
What are you doing?

44:58.698 --> 45:00.689
What is light?

45:01.450 --> 45:02.940
What is light?

45:04.745 --> 45:07.612
How important is light?

45:09.041 --> 45:11.123
OK, let's think about that for a minute.

45:11.294 --> 45:15.628
Cos it seems very basic and banal
but it's not. It's loaded.

45:15.798 --> 45:17.504
It's a bloody nail bomb.

45:18.384 --> 45:23.174
I think light is probably
the most important gift we have

45:23.347 --> 45:25.212
from the universe.

45:25.391 --> 45:28.679
And if you asked any intelligent
bloody writer,

45:29.478 --> 45:32.811
like Professor Hawking or anybody
of that ilk,

45:34.192 --> 45:36.183
he could talk to you...

45:36.736 --> 45:40.570
for about, I don't know, a year...

45:40.740 --> 45:42.901
just about bloody light!

45:43.492 --> 45:46.984
We don't want to be in the dark,

45:47.163 --> 45:48.903
being fiddled with.

45:49.081 --> 45:50.946
That's for sure.

45:51.125 --> 45:52.990
How's my dad meant to compete?

45:53.169 --> 45:55.034
The only time I saw him enthral a room

45:55.213 --> 45:58.831
was when he gave a talk about
the disappearance of a giant sturgeon.

45:59.050 --> 46:01.883
Sturgeons are royal fish,
since the 14th century,

46:02.053 --> 46:04.385
and, if caught,
they do become property of the Crown.

46:04.555 --> 46:07.388
So, yes, we're treating the matter
as suspicious.

46:09.644 --> 46:11.430
How deep is the ocean?

46:11.604 --> 46:15.938
Seven miles at its deepest point, but
on average, six miles as a rule of thumb.

46:16.484 --> 46:18.349
But no fish could live down there.

46:18.527 --> 46:21.894
There's no light, of course,
and the pressure is far too great.

46:22.073 --> 46:24.564
Any human who found themselves
at that level,

46:24.742 --> 46:26.607
well, they would die immediately.

46:26.786 --> 46:29.528
They would implode.
They wouldn't stand a chance.

46:29.705 --> 46:31.570
But in answer to your question,

46:31.749 --> 46:34.206
the ocean is six miles deep.

46:37.588 --> 46:39.419
I am a prism.

46:39.590 --> 46:41.581
That's not mad.

46:42.260 --> 46:45.172
OK? I am a prism, I am light.

46:45.888 --> 46:47.879
I am lucid.

46:48.474 --> 46:50.715
I am exciting and delicious.

46:50.893 --> 46:53.179
Thanks very much for today.
You've been fantastic.

47:07.618 --> 47:08.778
Well done.

47:08.953 --> 47:11.285
- It seemed to go pretty well.
- Oh, yes, yes.

47:11.455 --> 47:13.320
I think they...

47:13.499 --> 47:15.956
- They loved it.
- Did you enjoy it?

47:16.127 --> 47:17.788
Absolutely.

47:18.421 --> 47:19.957
A lot to take in.

47:20.131 --> 47:21.996
- But it was silly, right?
- No, no.

47:22.174 --> 47:24.085
- You think I'm silly?
- No, I don't.

47:24.260 --> 47:26.842
- It's OK.
- I don't. I don't.

47:27.680 --> 47:29.671
I didn't ask for this, Jill.

47:30.474 --> 47:33.637
This gift, it's ...
It's like a burden to me.

47:33.811 --> 47:34.675
Sure.

47:34.854 --> 47:37.220
Yeah, you must be exhausted.

47:39.942 --> 47:41.807
I split up with Kim-Lin.

47:41.986 --> 47:43.977
Oh, no. Oh, dear.

47:44.155 --> 47:45.941
Let her go.

47:46.115 --> 47:48.356
- She was young, right?
- I'm really sorry.

47:48.534 --> 47:51.446
- It's all good.
- Anyway, I'd better... I'd better go.

47:51.620 --> 47:53.656
- Gonna come next week?
- Er...

47:54.290 --> 47:56.281
- I can?
- You'd better.

47:56.459 --> 47:58.791
Sure, I'll check my diary.

47:58.961 --> 48:01.543
- Bring Lloyd.
- Um...

48:01.714 --> 48:03.705
OK. I don't think it's really...

48:05.343 --> 48:06.924
..his cup of... I'll ask.

48:07.094 --> 48:08.959
If you ask him...

48:09.138 --> 48:11.129
he will come.

48:14.185 --> 48:16.050
- I'll see what I can do.
- Right,

48:16.228 --> 48:18.935
- Thank you again. You're very good.
- Ciao, Jill.

48:19.106 --> 48:21.062
- Watch yourself.
- Thank you.

48:22.401 --> 48:24.392
Bye-bye.

48:34.288 --> 48:36.279
I'm watching you.

48:39.877 --> 48:42.368
And by being in balance
with the colours around them,

48:42.546 --> 48:44.753
with a healthy colour
glow around themselves,

48:44.924 --> 48:46.789
they're living a fulfilled life.

48:46.967 --> 48:52.382
So when you're in a crisis, it doesn't
feel like the waves are crashing on you,

48:52.848 --> 48:56.466
it feels like you can just stand
under those waves

48:56.644 --> 48:58.509
and let them do their business,

48:58.687 --> 49:03.772
and then get a towel and bloody dry
yourself off, and go about your day.

49:03.943 --> 49:05.353
That's what it means.

49:06.153 --> 49:07.563
My mum is the exact type of person

49:07.738 --> 49:10.150
who is susceptible
to this mystic bullshit.

49:10.324 --> 49:12.064
I can picture her
telling Jackie at work

49:12.243 --> 49:13.403
how it's a bit over the top

49:13.577 --> 49:15.067
but there's something in it.

49:15.246 --> 49:17.111
If my dad radiated a colour,

49:17.289 --> 49:19.325
it'd be ochre or eggshell.

49:20.543 --> 49:23.501
He knows the number for the pothole
helpline off by heart.

49:23.671 --> 49:26.663
It's about a foot in diameter.
It's a bit of a concern.

49:27.508 --> 49:28.588
Pothole.

49:28.759 --> 49:31.546
Yes, that's right, Lloyd Tate.
Oh, hi, how are you?

49:31.720 --> 49:35.429
He was the first person in our village
to install double glazing.

49:38.602 --> 49:39.682
It's from Dad.

49:39.854 --> 49:41.719
He ruins every Christmas.

49:41.897 --> 49:43.888
It's a kettle.

49:45.109 --> 49:45.973
Great.

49:46.152 --> 49:48.564
..how extraordinary they are.

49:49.405 --> 49:51.396
Because they've forgotten, right?

49:52.450 --> 49:55.032
Maybe it's time for Dad
to rip off his vest again.

49:55.202 --> 49:58.444
I mean, it's a bit over the top,
but I think there's something in it.

49:58.622 --> 50:00.283
Yes, yes. Good turnout, was it?

50:00.458 --> 50:02.039
I'm going out for a bit.

50:02.793 --> 50:06.331
The question was, do I tell Jordana
about this Graham situation?

50:06.505 --> 50:08.370
I mean, we'd had sex.

50:08.549 --> 50:11.416
Wouldn't it spoil things
if I suddenly got emotional?

50:14.805 --> 50:17.672
I decided to soften the blow
with some light arson.

50:22.480 --> 50:24.596
You don't talk about your parents much.

50:24.773 --> 50:28.686
- I mean, do they get on?
- Yeah, they get on.

50:28.861 --> 50:30.394
Mine get on as well.

50:30.415 --> 50:33.030
It's good, isn't it?
It's important that they get on.

50:33.702 --> 50:36.264
So everything's fine at home,
everything's OK?

50:36.390 --> 50:37.820
Cos everything's fine with me.

50:39.038 --> 50:41.120
Actually, my mum's not well
at the moment.

50:41.290 --> 50:42.951
They get on, you know.

50:43.125 --> 50:44.706
That's the main thing.

50:45.669 --> 50:46.829
Yeah.

50:49.089 --> 50:51.205
Sorry, did you say your mum wasn't well?

50:51.383 --> 50:52.247
Yeah.

50:53.928 --> 50:55.919
Why, what's wrong?

50:56.764 --> 50:58.629
She's got...

50:58.807 --> 51:01.844
it's called...medulloblastoma.

51:06.607 --> 51:08.268
What does it mean?

51:09.360 --> 51:11.351
It means she's got a brain tumour.

51:15.115 --> 51:16.525
Oh, no.

51:20.704 --> 51:23.456
Confiding in Jordana was now impossible.

51:24.258 --> 51:25.739
Her mother had cancer.

51:25.909 --> 51:28.402
And in the Top Trumps
of parental problems,

51:28.526 --> 51:30.594
cancer beats potential infidelity.

51:31.924 --> 51:34.210
I would have to
travel this road secretly,

51:34.385 --> 51:36.046
unaided,

51:36.220 --> 51:37.960
a renegade,

51:38.138 --> 51:40.049
a solitary samurai.

52:14.091 --> 52:16.628
Things were a lot less fun since
Jordana's mother might die

52:16.802 --> 52:19.464
and my parents' marriage
started falling apart.

52:19.638 --> 52:22.254
I've been working on strategies
to solve both problems.

52:22.433 --> 52:25.971
I bought my dad some new aftershave,
but I'm drawing a blank on the cancer.

52:30.983 --> 52:34.191
You're fucked. Even if her mum
is terminal, it can still take ages.

52:34.361 --> 52:35.601
Please, Chip, shut up.

52:35.779 --> 52:37.519
This is not what you signed up for.

52:37.698 --> 52:40.531
This is about dipping your wick.
You've done that, game over.

52:40.701 --> 52:42.783
She'll be in no mood
to put out any more.

52:42.953 --> 52:44.363
No more Yuletide logging for you,

52:44.538 --> 52:47.780
unlike me, who shall be rolling in it
throughout the festive period.

52:47.958 --> 52:49.914
Do you actually pre-prepare these lines?

52:50.085 --> 52:51.950
I just split lines as they come to me.

52:52.129 --> 52:54.916
You've got to shut the shit down.
Keiron, get my back.

52:55.090 --> 52:56.921
- With extreme prejudice.
- Thank you.

52:57.092 --> 53:00.300
- Nothing's changed.
- Do what you want. Remember two things:

53:00.471 --> 53:02.302
one - treat 'em mean, keep 'em keen.

53:02.473 --> 53:04.338
Two - don't mix family and bush.

53:04.516 --> 53:07.804
Get the fuck out of here.
Merry Christmas. Have a good 'un.

53:09.021 --> 53:10.306
You all right?

53:10.481 --> 53:13.848
You've gotta shut this shit down.
It's fucking ridiculous.

53:18.322 --> 53:20.313
♪ ALEX TURNER: Glass In The Park

53:27.414 --> 53:29.996
♪ If there's glass in the park

53:31.251 --> 53:35.494
♪ Darling, I can't help but keep

53:36.048 --> 53:40.087
♪ Making appointments to sweep

53:40.260 --> 53:44.094
♪ Beneath the climbing frame

53:46.016 --> 53:49.679
♪ If the sun's in your eyes

53:50.270 --> 53:54.513
♪ I'll tighten your blindfold, baby

53:55.109 --> 53:59.273
♪ Don't worry, your foot won't get cut

53:59.446 --> 54:02.938
♪ Strut carelessly

54:04.034 --> 54:06.741
I've been taking my duty as a boyfriend
seriously.

54:06.912 --> 54:09.699
Last night, I reread the book
I Only Want What's Best For You.

54:09.873 --> 54:11.363
I remembered a chapter that says:

54:20.459 --> 54:22.303
It's therefore in Jordana's interest

54:22.315 --> 54:24.421
that her dog dies before her mother does.

54:25.180 --> 54:27.045
Then we can get things back on track.

54:33.564 --> 54:35.395
Oliver Tate.

54:35.566 --> 54:37.557
OK, calm down.

54:38.736 --> 54:41.603
What happened?

54:42.990 --> 54:45.197
There was no need
to poison Jordana's dog

54:45.367 --> 54:47.858
because Jordana's dog
had just been hit by a train.

54:48.036 --> 54:50.903
I scraped his remains
into the bin liner I'd brought.

54:51.081 --> 54:54.573
The death of a pet makes it easier
to accept the death of a parent.

54:54.752 --> 54:58.415
I could feel the tension between Jordana
and I start to slip away.

55:12.436 --> 55:13.300
Oh!

55:13.479 --> 55:15.640
No, of course, I'm sorry. I just...

55:15.814 --> 55:17.805
I thought...

55:19.985 --> 55:21.976
We should bury him.

55:23.280 --> 55:24.941
No, I don't think we should.

55:25.115 --> 55:27.276
Foxes dig up dead animals and eat them.

55:28.619 --> 55:30.610
What should we do, then?

55:33.165 --> 55:35.907
Well, there's this thing the Vikings
used to do.

55:44.802 --> 55:46.667
Jude would like to meet you.

55:46.845 --> 55:48.551
- Who's Jude?
- My mum.

55:48.722 --> 55:50.462
Since when have you called her Jude?

55:50.641 --> 55:52.472
Since she might die in two weeks.

55:52.643 --> 55:53.928
Right.

55:54.978 --> 55:56.969
So, do you wanna come?

56:01.860 --> 56:05.273
The Bevans had Christmas dinner early
in case it was the last one they had.

56:05.447 --> 56:07.654
I hoped it wouldn't be,
cos the turkey was quite dry

56:07.825 --> 56:10.362
and the spouts had turned mushy
and out of focus.

56:10.536 --> 56:11.821
This is crackin', love.

56:11.995 --> 56:13.656
Yeah, it's great. Thank you, Mrs Bevan.

56:13.831 --> 56:16.288
This is my last warning. It's Jude.

56:16.458 --> 56:19.746
So, I hear from my little girl
that you've stolen her heart.

56:19.920 --> 56:20.625
Dad...

56:20.796 --> 56:23.538
Let me tell you,
if you're lucky enough to find an angel,

56:26.593 --> 56:29.005
hold onto her
with everything you've got.

56:30.597 --> 56:32.588
Oh, these fucking lights!

56:35.727 --> 56:37.718
Cheap shit.

56:41.400 --> 56:43.391
Oh, come on.

56:44.361 --> 56:48.070
You're acting like I'm dead already.

56:48.240 --> 56:49.525
Come on.

56:49.700 --> 56:51.941
It'd take more than
some silly tumour to kill me.

56:52.119 --> 56:54.781
- It might not.
- Oh, come on, now. Don't be daft.

56:57.416 --> 56:59.407
- Sorry.
- All right.

57:00.002 --> 57:01.993
Oh, it's all right, darling. Ssh.

57:03.589 --> 57:04.704
- Come here.
- Sorry, love.

57:04.882 --> 57:06.088
Are you all right? Come on.

57:06.258 --> 57:07.623
- Come on.
- Sorry, sorry.

57:07.801 --> 57:08.540
Sorry.

57:08.719 --> 57:09.754
- All right?
- Yeah.

57:09.928 --> 57:12.044
I'm fine. I'm fine. Give us a cudge.

57:12.890 --> 57:14.551
Listen... Thank you.

57:14.725 --> 57:16.340
Thank you from the bottom of my heart.

57:16.518 --> 57:19.806
Thank you for looking after Jordana,
for walking through the fire with her.

57:19.980 --> 57:21.595
- Thank you. Appreciate it.
- No.

57:21.773 --> 57:23.980
- No, we both do.
- He's a good boy, isn't he?

57:24.151 --> 57:25.641
Part of the family now. Deal?

57:25.819 --> 57:27.104
- Deal?
- Deal.

57:27.279 --> 57:28.564
Family, deal.

57:28.739 --> 57:29.899
Deal, yes?

57:30.073 --> 57:32.109
There we fucking go.

57:52.930 --> 57:55.797
Maybe you should come to the hospital
this Friday.

57:57.059 --> 58:00.017
Mum will have had her operation by then
and we can visit.

58:00.187 --> 58:03.600
- If you felt like it.
- Er, Friday.

58:04.358 --> 58:06.019
I've got to do some Christmas shopping.

58:06.193 --> 58:07.603
- What?
- I always leave it too late.

58:07.778 --> 58:10.064
- I want to get you something good.
- Mother might die.

58:10.238 --> 58:11.273
- I know.
- Do you care,

58:11.448 --> 58:13.439
- or couldn't you give a fuck?
- I do, clearly.

58:13.617 --> 58:15.073
I'll come. When is it?

58:15.243 --> 58:16.983
Friday.

58:18.664 --> 58:19.904
Great, yeah.

58:20.082 --> 58:23.870
Yeah, Friday's good for me, actually.
Yeah, I can do that. Excellent.

58:24.044 --> 58:26.251
Your skin's better.
You're allergic to the dog.

58:27.047 --> 58:28.537
I'm eating better.

58:28.715 --> 58:30.125
Following Mum's special diet.

58:30.300 --> 58:32.211
Is that because of the...

58:32.386 --> 58:34.251
We eat lots of ginger now.

58:34.429 --> 58:36.420
So, Friday.

58:37.099 --> 58:38.760
The visiting hours are six till eight.

58:38.934 --> 58:41.767
Got it. Six till eight.
I'll meet you there.

58:41.937 --> 58:43.068
OK.

58:43.939 --> 58:46.006
I'm sorry I'm like this.

58:46.566 --> 58:49.103
- I dunno. I'm sorry.
- No, it's fine.

58:49.277 --> 58:50.926
Don't think you have to wait. It's cold.

58:50.927 --> 58:52.724
No, it's fine. I'll wait.

58:53.448 --> 58:55.063
I've got you these matches.

58:55.242 --> 58:57.233
Your favourite.

58:58.704 --> 59:00.285
I noticed the way you light a match.

59:00.455 --> 59:02.992
The flame is the same shape
as a falling tear.

59:04.001 --> 59:06.083
I knew then it was too late to save her.

59:06.837 --> 59:08.919
She'd gone gooey in the middle.

59:09.089 --> 59:12.126
From now on she'll buy little gifts
for her favourite teachers

59:12.300 --> 59:15.633
and she'll admire the scenery
and she'll buy soup for homeless people.

59:16.263 --> 59:18.675
And she'll never burn my leg here again.

59:22.060 --> 59:24.221
- Maybe I will go. It's pretty cold.
- Yeah.

59:24.396 --> 59:26.432
OK.

59:35.073 --> 59:37.064
Good night.

59:53.341 --> 59:56.708
When I discovered
I could see these colours in people,

59:56.887 --> 01:00:00.004
it took a long time because I was
in such a state of anxiety.

01:00:00.182 --> 01:00:04.642
It was when I started to be comfortable
with it and stopped trying to resist it,

01:00:04.811 --> 01:00:06.676
it started to nourish me.

01:00:06.855 --> 01:00:09.267
And I could relax around it
and be in it.

01:00:09.441 --> 01:00:13.059
Then I started to make
more of an understanding of it.

01:00:18.366 --> 01:00:20.652
Well, it's um...

01:00:20.827 --> 01:00:22.818
It's interesting.

01:00:24.539 --> 01:00:27.155
He's really working that third eye,
isn't he?

01:00:28.085 --> 01:00:30.246
It's just a metaphor, Lloyd.

01:00:30.420 --> 01:00:32.536
Oh, no, no, no. I mean, it's good, yes.

01:00:33.799 --> 01:00:35.960
I like the whole colour coding thing.

01:00:36.134 --> 01:00:39.171
Well, I'd like to go again.

01:00:39.346 --> 01:00:41.337
I'd like you to be there, so...

01:00:43.183 --> 01:00:46.971
- You want us to go?
- Yes, I do.

01:00:47.729 --> 01:00:49.139
Right.

01:00:49.314 --> 01:00:50.895
Do I have to bring shorts?

01:00:51.066 --> 01:00:55.059
- It's on this Friday, so...
- Right, OK, yeah.

01:00:58.240 --> 01:01:00.231
What, are you coming or...

01:01:00.951 --> 01:01:03.988
Well, I'm intrigued, yeah.

01:01:04.162 --> 01:01:06.323
- For sure.
- This Friday. This Friday.

01:01:06.498 --> 01:01:07.533
- This Friday?
- Mm-hm.

01:01:07.707 --> 01:01:09.572
OK, yep, yep.

01:01:10.752 --> 01:01:12.993
- Thank you.
- Mm.

01:01:13.755 --> 01:01:15.336
Don't let me down. OK?

01:01:15.507 --> 01:01:18.749
The most fantastical way people
experience the Graham T Purvis system

01:01:18.927 --> 01:01:20.167
is to come to the seminar.

01:01:20.345 --> 01:01:22.336
Oliver, what are you doing?

01:01:24.182 --> 01:01:26.389
..have been mind-blowing.
I've seen lives change.

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:28.551
It's just incredible.

01:01:29.187 --> 01:01:35.103
I wish on a global scale
that people could get the message.

01:01:35.277 --> 01:01:38.110
Wouldn't it be just wonderful?

01:01:40.448 --> 01:01:42.109
Friday...

01:01:42.284 --> 01:01:44.320
I'll be OK. I'll be...

